1
00:00:00,700 --> 00:00:06,540
Tell me if this sounds familiar: you have
a signal to trade, you enter, you place your

2
00:00:06,540 --> 00:00:11,190
stop loss and take profit and then price goes
in the opposite direction.

3
00:00:11,190 --> 00:00:16,299
And then you pray for the chance to close
your trade at breakeven.

4
00:00:16,299 --> 00:00:21,800
You hope that price will return to your entry
point, just to close that bad trade.

5
00:00:21,800 --> 00:00:25,199
This is you, trapped in a losing position.

6
00:00:25,199 --> 00:00:26,860
And your entry point, is your salvation.

7
00:00:26,860 --> 00:00:30,109
That’s the psychology of a trapped trader.

8
00:00:30,109 --> 00:00:37,559
In today’s video, I’ll show how to take
advantage of trapped traders and how to identify

9
00:00:37,559 --> 00:00:44,170
key areas on a chart where traders are anxious
and eager to exit their losing trades.

10
00:00:44,170 --> 00:00:49,110
It’s gonna be interesting, so, like, subscribe,
and stick around for the full video.

11
00:00:49,110 --> 00:00:55,200
The psychology of a trapped trader

12
00:00:55,200 --> 00:01:00,540
When you place a trade, you expect the market
to move in the direction you anticipate.

13
00:01:00,540 --> 00:01:05,790
If the market begins moving in the opposite
direction, your fear takes over.

14
00:01:05,790 --> 00:01:10,670
You will continue to hold the losing trade,
but hoping the market could still come back

15
00:01:10,670 --> 00:01:12,630
to your entry point.

16
00:01:12,630 --> 00:01:17,500
On some occasions the market will end up coming
back to where you entered.

17
00:01:17,500 --> 00:01:24,310
And you will be able to close your trade at
a small loss or even better, at break-even.

18
00:01:24,310 --> 00:01:29,820
Unfortunately the vast majority of the time,
the market doesn’t come back and instead

19
00:01:29,820 --> 00:01:34,700
continues to move further and further away
from the entry point.

20
00:01:34,700 --> 00:01:38,320
True story: that’s exactly how I blew my
first account.

21
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:43,030
I waited and waited for the market to return
to my entry level.

22
00:01:43,030 --> 00:01:49,470
And at some point, the loss became so large
and I received a margin call.

23
00:01:49,470 --> 00:01:55,930
A trader trapped in a losing position is forced
to take an emotional trading decision.

24
00:01:55,930 --> 00:02:01,630
Your goal is to identify and trade against
the positions of such traders.

25
00:02:01,630 --> 00:02:07,850
You capitalize on the vulnerable traders who
are caught on the wrong side of the market.

26
00:02:07,850 --> 00:02:14,830
So let’s see where you can find traders
holding losing positions in the market.

27
00:02:14,830 --> 00:02:22,000
LONG CANDLES
There is one event in which you can be sure

28
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,000
retail traders will place trades.

29
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:31,690
This event is when the market makes a large
move in one direction, a large range candle.

30
00:02:31,690 --> 00:02:35,500
These candles always make traders place trades.

31
00:02:35,500 --> 00:02:40,750
When you see a large range candle form in
the market, a big number of traders will place

32
00:02:40,750 --> 00:02:44,640
trades in the direction of the candle.

33
00:02:44,640 --> 00:02:48,970
If the market begins to move in the opposite
direction to which the large range candle

34
00:02:48,970 --> 00:02:55,230
has formed, then all of the traders who have
placed trades will become trapped in losing

35
00:02:55,230 --> 00:02:57,340
trades.

36
00:02:57,340 --> 00:02:59,540
How do you take advantage of this situation?

37
00:02:59,540 --> 00:03:06,920
We’ll you know that their biggest desire
is for price to return to their entry level.

38
00:03:06,920 --> 00:03:15,470
In this example, after this big green candle,
lots if traders were trapped around this area.

39
00:03:15,470 --> 00:03:20,200
If the market continues to move against these
traders, at some point.

40
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:23,030
some of them will close their positions.

41
00:03:23,030 --> 00:03:28,370
But a lot of them will wait for a breakeven
chance.

42
00:03:28,370 --> 00:03:33,420
And look what happened when price returned
to the previous level.

43
00:03:33,420 --> 00:03:36,190
You see the immediate reaction?

44
00:03:36,190 --> 00:03:38,360
Price rejected the level aggressively.

45
00:03:38,360 --> 00:03:45,480
That’s because the losing traders finally
had their chance to exit their trades.

46
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:52,049
You want to find those areas on the chart,
and open position when losing traders close

47
00:03:52,049 --> 00:03:53,450
their trades.

48
00:03:53,450 --> 00:03:56,239
LARGE WICKS

49
00:03:56,239 --> 00:04:06,450
In many cases, large range candles often turn
into a different type of candle before they

50
00:04:06,450 --> 00:04:07,450
close.

51
00:04:07,450 --> 00:04:10,500
The candle they turn into is a pin bar.

52
00:04:10,500 --> 00:04:15,450
When pin bars are forming, they will look
heavily bullish or bearish, depending on the

53
00:04:15,450 --> 00:04:17,459
type of pin.

54
00:04:17,459 --> 00:04:22,820
But when big players come in, the candle which
initially looked really bullish or really

55
00:04:22,820 --> 00:04:25,181
bearish, now has a large wick on it.

56
00:04:25,181 --> 00:04:34,110
The wick contains the traders who are now
trapped in losing trades.

57
00:04:34,110 --> 00:04:39,740
The longer the wick (or shadow) of the bar,
the better because it indicates the wrong

58
00:04:39,740 --> 00:04:43,720
movement which has prevailed in the market.

59
00:04:43,720 --> 00:04:51,050
Look at this example, there are many wick,
but this one stands out the most.

60
00:04:51,050 --> 00:04:55,400
This would be the main wick I would try to
trade.

61
00:04:55,400 --> 00:05:00,930
This would be the “point of pain”, the
point where losing traders would happily exit

62
00:05:00,930 --> 00:05:03,970
their trades.

63
00:05:03,970 --> 00:05:10,000
Notice how price challenged the area of the
pin bar, and look what happened.

64
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:18,229
We have a first, small, rejection, and another
one, this time much bigger.

65
00:05:18,229 --> 00:05:23,169
A long trade here would have been a decent
trade.

66
00:05:23,169 --> 00:05:29,670
You enter a buy position, where other traders
close their previous sell positions.

67
00:05:29,670 --> 00:05:33,530
This adds momentum, to your trade.

68
00:05:33,530 --> 00:05:41,259
FALSE BREAKOUTS
A false breakout is when price moves beyond

69
00:05:41,259 --> 00:05:46,259
the previously established level and then
retreats back below it.

70
00:05:46,259 --> 00:05:52,169
And of course, after a false breakout, many
traders will be trapped on the wrong side

71
00:05:52,169 --> 00:05:54,020
of the market.

72
00:05:54,020 --> 00:05:59,660
If we look at this example, from a typical
retail traders’ perspective, you can understand

73
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:05,380
why such a large amount of traders became
trapped in losing trades.

74
00:06:05,380 --> 00:06:11,190
To begin with, the market was advancing higher
which made many traders believe the market

75
00:06:11,190 --> 00:06:14,160
was in a strong up-trend.

76
00:06:14,160 --> 00:06:19,840
As the price climbed higher, a bullish large
range candle started to form, which made the

77
00:06:19,840 --> 00:06:26,039
retail traders think they were seeing a significant
up-move taking place.

78
00:06:26,039 --> 00:06:32,170
As a huge mass of retail traders started to
buy, smart money saw an opportunity to take

79
00:06:32,170 --> 00:06:38,789
profits of their own buy trades using the
buy orders from the retail traders.

80
00:06:38,789 --> 00:06:44,490
That resulted into a false breakout and the
retail traders are now stuck in losing long

81
00:06:44,490 --> 00:06:45,490
positions.

82
00:06:45,490 --> 00:06:51,470
And, look what happened the next time price
reached the previous level.

83
00:06:51,470 --> 00:06:54,310
An immediate reaction.

84
00:06:54,310 --> 00:07:01,030
Losing traders had their chance of exiting
their trades, which drove the market down.

85
00:07:01,030 --> 00:07:07,080
Again, you want to target this area, for a
short entry.

86
00:07:07,080 --> 00:07:15,699
BREAKOUTS WITHOUT RE-TEST
A breakout of an important level, with a large

87
00:07:15,699 --> 00:07:22,389
body candle, without a retest, is another
situation, during which a lot of traders are

88
00:07:22,389 --> 00:07:23,389
trapped.

89
00:07:23,389 --> 00:07:26,410
Let’s analyze this chart.

90
00:07:26,410 --> 00:07:30,890
Price fell aggressively right through the
support level.

91
00:07:30,890 --> 00:07:34,530
The breakout candle was a big red candlestick.

92
00:07:34,530 --> 00:07:37,900
No chance of retest whatsoever.

93
00:07:37,900 --> 00:07:41,270
As price continues to drop, buyers are trapped.

94
00:07:41,270 --> 00:07:46,970
They wait for the price to climb back up,
to exit their trades in the hopes of limiting

95
00:07:46,970 --> 00:07:48,909
their losses.

96
00:07:48,909 --> 00:07:55,659
The short traders are now happy and may consider
adding to their positions if the price revisits

97
00:07:55,659 --> 00:07:57,349
the price level.

98
00:07:57,349 --> 00:08:03,220
Lastly, the traders who did not enter the
market yet may go short if the price comes

99
00:08:03,220 --> 00:08:08,940
back to the previous support level, in anticipation
of prices dropping further.

100
00:08:08,940 --> 00:08:14,560
And of course, look at the reaction at the
level.

101
00:08:14,560 --> 00:08:19,389
Human emotions play a big part in the price
action observed in markets.

102
00:08:19,389 --> 00:08:26,080
A price chart can be seen of as a timeline
of optimism and pessimism.

103
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:33,250
It illustrates how market participants react
to changing future expectations.

104
00:08:33,250 --> 00:08:38,080
ACCUMULATION/DISTRIBUTION ZONES

105
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:44,580
When you see a range or consolidation in a
chart while there is average to high volume,

106
00:08:44,580 --> 00:08:50,350
the market is in the process of accumulating
enough trapped traders, before it can shake

107
00:08:50,350 --> 00:08:54,019
out of that area and make another move.

108
00:08:54,019 --> 00:08:59,480
In this example, we see an accumulation zone.

109
00:08:59,480 --> 00:09:07,370
We see price breaking below support, before
moving in the opposite direction.

110
00:09:07,370 --> 00:09:13,660
This is called a spring, in Wyckoff’s terms,
a pattern which traps any bearish breakout

111
00:09:13,660 --> 00:09:16,690
traders in a losing trade.

112
00:09:16,690 --> 00:09:24,519
It also traps the bulls out of their long
trades, if they have their stop loss below

113
00:09:24,519 --> 00:09:27,959
the consolidation.

114
00:09:27,959 --> 00:09:31,589
Often you’ll see patterns of an up thrust.

115
00:09:31,589 --> 00:09:38,209
Which is a breakout of the distribution pattern
at the top of an uptrend, which then reverses

116
00:09:38,209 --> 00:09:39,580
and heads down.

117
00:09:39,580 --> 00:09:43,899
In this example, here’s the distribution
zone.

118
00:09:43,899 --> 00:09:51,890
An up thrust is simply a false breakout of
the consolidation area, this green candle,

119
00:09:51,890 --> 00:09:54,930
where weaker hands expect a breakout.

120
00:09:54,930 --> 00:10:00,790
The market breaks out of the consolidation
only to return within the range.

121
00:10:00,790 --> 00:10:06,180
The following candles trap long traders in
a losing position.

122
00:10:06,180 --> 00:10:13,420
Now, during accumulation and distribution
phases, we can’t use the same strategy as

123
00:10:13,420 --> 00:10:17,399
before to take advantage of trapped traders.

124
00:10:17,399 --> 00:10:23,160
We can’t wait for price to return at the
previous spring level to enter, it would be

125
00:10:23,160 --> 00:10:24,710
too late.

126
00:10:24,710 --> 00:10:31,519
Generally speaking, the accumulation phase
forms as institutional traders increase their

127
00:10:31,519 --> 00:10:34,020
buying and drive demand.

128
00:10:34,020 --> 00:10:42,149
After the spring, as more interest develops,
the trading range displays higher lows as

129
00:10:42,149 --> 00:10:46,200
prices position themselves to move higher.

130
00:10:46,200 --> 00:10:51,380
You want to be in the market at the beginning
of a markup phase.

131
00:10:51,380 --> 00:10:58,120
With buyers gaining power, prices push through
the upper level of the trading range.

132
00:10:58,120 --> 00:11:05,100
At this Markup phase, the market will show
a consistent upward trend.

133
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:10,250
MARKET GAPS

134
00:11:10,250 --> 00:11:16,930
When a gap occurs, usually on stock market,
you can bet a lot of traders remained trapped

135
00:11:16,930 --> 00:11:19,579
in their positions.

136
00:11:19,579 --> 00:11:24,420
You could say that the price “jumped”
a certain distance, meaning that it closed

137
00:11:24,420 --> 00:11:31,019
at one price, and then opened higher or lower,
without touching the intervening levels.

138
00:11:31,019 --> 00:11:36,950
There’s a saying among market participants
that “all gaps need to be filled”.

139
00:11:36,950 --> 00:11:43,880
A gap “getting filled” is when price action
at a later time retraces to the last closing

140
00:11:43,880 --> 00:11:47,650
price preceding the gap.

141
00:11:47,650 --> 00:11:54,420
Once it’s retraced fully, then the gap is
considered filled.

142
00:11:54,420 --> 00:12:01,040
Gaps usually form as a result of low liquidity,
as the market closes and then reopens the

143
00:12:01,040 --> 00:12:02,480
next day.

144
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:08,230
When gaps form overnight, it’s a sign that
the market sentiment has shifted.

145
00:12:08,230 --> 00:12:13,250
Market participants are no longer willing
to pay the same price on the open of the next

146
00:12:13,250 --> 00:12:16,850
day, as they were on the previous close.

147
00:12:16,850 --> 00:12:22,139
Many times, at least when it comes to the
bigger gaps, it’s a sign that new information

148
00:12:22,139 --> 00:12:27,750
has been released and taken into account by
market participants.

149
00:12:27,750 --> 00:12:33,500
When we have a gap, lots of traders are trapped
in losing positions.

150
00:12:33,500 --> 00:12:40,589
And when the gap is filled, and price reaches
the “point of pain” of many losing trades,

151
00:12:40,589 --> 00:12:42,660
you will often see an immediate reaction.

152
00:12:42,660 --> 00:12:46,000
That’s one of my favorite setups.

153
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:53,230
A gap which is filled, combined maybe with
another level of confluence, makes for a decent

154
00:12:53,230 --> 00:12:58,670
trade to take advantage of losing traders.

155
00:12:58,670 --> 00:13:04,970
Pullback trap

156
00:13:04,970 --> 00:13:09,680
Markets move in waves with impulsive and corrective
moves.

157
00:13:09,680 --> 00:13:16,389
A very popular trading method is trading the
corrective move and entering a trade in the

158
00:13:16,389 --> 00:13:21,949
direction of the trend, once the corrective
move signals completion.

159
00:13:21,949 --> 00:13:29,079
The issue is that many traders are impatient
and don't want to risk not being in the move.

160
00:13:29,079 --> 00:13:35,980
So they enter trades too early at the first
sign of completion.

161
00:13:35,980 --> 00:13:42,639
But what may appear to be a simple pullback
will actually be a complex pullback on a lower

162
00:13:42,639 --> 00:13:45,570
time frame.

163
00:13:45,570 --> 00:13:52,029
The first wave indicates the first leg of
this pullback and the pin bar looks like it

164
00:13:52,029 --> 00:13:56,370
could indicate a resumption of the up trend.

165
00:13:56,370 --> 00:14:02,110
Traders enter and place their stop below the
candle.

166
00:14:02,110 --> 00:14:08,860
Price then turns around and makes a second
wave, and traps long traders.

167
00:14:08,860 --> 00:14:14,630
Being on the right side of those moves can
move your positions into profit very quickly.

168
00:14:14,630 --> 00:14:21,720
Again, the key is to see where traders may
be on the wrong side of the market and get

169
00:14:21,720 --> 00:15:37,130
yourself positioned, to take advantage of
them when they have to exit their losing trades.

170
